{"type":"tool_execution_end","toolCallId":"call_fa9d9891ce164aa59e2eeece","toolName":"mcp","result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 25\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619230546\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 886656\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":25,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619230546\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\\n\\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\\n\\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\\n\\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\\n\\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\\n\\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\\n\\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\\n\\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\\n\\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\\n\\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\\n\\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\\n\\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn the word \\\"airports\\\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\\n\\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\\n\\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\\n\\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\\n\\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\\n\\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\\n\\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\\n\\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\\n\\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\\n\\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\\n\\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\\n\\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\\n\\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\\"\\n- \\\"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\\"\\n- \\\"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\\"\\n- \\\"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\\"\\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\\nSource: Abdi Media, \\\"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n- \\\"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\\"\\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\\nSource: OPSGROUP, \\\"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\\\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Under the Iran section: \\\"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\\\"\\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \\\"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\\\"\\n- Under May: \\\"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\\\"\\n- Under April 21: \\\"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\\\"\\n\\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\\nBytes: 1970\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\\nBytes: 1631\\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\\nBytes: 1785\\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\\nBytes: 1492\\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":886656,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":25}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 25\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619230546\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 886656\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":25,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619230546\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\\n\\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\\n\\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\\n\\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\\n\\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\\n\\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\\n\\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\\n\\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\\n\\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\\n\\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\\n\\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\\n\\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn the word \\\"airports\\\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\\n\\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\\n\\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\\n\\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\\n\\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\\n\\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\\n\\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\\n\\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\\n\\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\\n\\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\\n\\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\\n\\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\\n\\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\\"\\n- \\\"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\\"\\n- \\\"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\\"\\n- \\\"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\\"\\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\\nSource: Abdi Media, \\\"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n- \\\"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\\"\\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\\nSource: OPSGROUP, \\\"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\\\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Under the Iran section: \\\"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\\\"\\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \\\"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\\\"\\n- Under May: \\\"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\\\"\\n- Under April 21: \\\"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\\\"\\n\\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\\nBytes: 1970\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\\nBytes: 1631\\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\\nBytes: 1785\\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\\nBytes: 1492\\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":886656,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":25}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":25,"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260619230546","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\n\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\n\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\n\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\n\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\n\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\n\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\n\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\n\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\n\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\n\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\n\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\n\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\n\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\n\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\n\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\n\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\n\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\n\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\n\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\n\nThe defense tries to turn the word \"airports\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\n\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\n\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\n\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\n\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\n\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\n\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\n\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\n\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\n\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\n\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\n\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\n\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\n\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\n\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\n\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\n\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\n\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\nSource: Indian Express, \"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- \"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\"\n- \"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\"\n- \"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\"\n- \"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\"\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\n\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\nSource: Abdi Media, \"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- \"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\"\n- \"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\"\n- \"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\"\n- \"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\"\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\n\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\nSource: OPSGROUP, \"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Under the Iran section: \"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\"\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\"\n- Under May: \"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\"\n- Under April 21: \"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\"\n\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\n\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\nBytes: 1970\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\nBytes: 1631\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\nBytes: 1785\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\n\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\nBytes: 1492\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\n\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":886656,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":16,"version":25}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"}},"isError":false}
{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_fa9d9891ce164aa59e2eeece","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 25\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619230546\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 886656\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":25,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619230546\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\\n\\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\\n\\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\\n\\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\\n\\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\\n\\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\\n\\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\\n\\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\\n\\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\\n\\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\\n\\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\\n\\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn the word \\\"airports\\\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\\n\\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\\n\\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\\n\\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\\n\\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\\n\\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\\n\\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\\n\\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\\n\\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\\n\\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\\n\\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\\n\\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\\n\\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\\"\\n- \\\"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\\"\\n- \\\"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\\"\\n- \\\"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\\"\\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\\nSource: Abdi Media, \\\"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n- \\\"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\\"\\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\\nSource: OPSGROUP, \\\"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\\\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Under the Iran section: \\\"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\\\"\\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \\\"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\\\"\\n- Under May: \\\"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\\\"\\n- Under April 21: \\\"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\\\"\\n\\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\\nBytes: 1970\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\\nBytes: 1631\\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\\nBytes: 1785\\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\\nBytes: 1492\\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":886656,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":25}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 25\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619230546\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 886656\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":25,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619230546\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\\n\\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\\n\\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\\n\\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\\n\\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\\n\\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\\n\\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\\n\\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\\n\\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\\n\\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\\n\\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\\n\\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn the word \\\"airports\\\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\\n\\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\\n\\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\\n\\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\\n\\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\\n\\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\\n\\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\\n\\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\\n\\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\\n\\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\\n\\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\\n\\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\\n\\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\\"\\n- \\\"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\\"\\n- \\\"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\\"\\n- \\\"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\\"\\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\\nSource: Abdi Media, \\\"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n- \\\"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\\"\\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\\nSource: OPSGROUP, \\\"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\\\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Under the Iran section: \\\"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\\\"\\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \\\"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\\\"\\n- Under May: \\\"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\\\"\\n- Under April 21: \\\"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\\\"\\n\\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\\nBytes: 1970\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\\nBytes: 1631\\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\\nBytes: 1785\\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\\nBytes: 1492\\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":886656,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":25}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":25,"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260619230546","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\n\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\n\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\n\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\n\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\n\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\n\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\n\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\n\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\n\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\n\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\n\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\n\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\n\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\n\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\n\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\n\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\n\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\n\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\n\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\n\nThe defense tries to turn the word \"airports\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\n\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\n\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\n\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\n\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\n\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\n\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\n\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\n\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\n\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\n\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\n\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\n\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\n\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\n\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\n\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\n\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\n\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\nSource: Indian Express, \"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- \"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\"\n- \"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\"\n- \"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\"\n- \"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\"\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\n\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\nSource: Abdi Media, \"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- \"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\"\n- \"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\"\n- \"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\"\n- \"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\"\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\n\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\nSource: OPSGROUP, \"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Under the Iran section: \"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\"\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\"\n- Under May: \"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\"\n- Under April 21: \"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\"\n\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\n\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\nBytes: 1970\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\nBytes: 1631\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\nBytes: 1785\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\n\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\nBytes: 1492\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\n\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":886656,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":16,"version":25}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781911523427}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_fa9d9891ce164aa59e2eeece","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 25\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619230546\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 886656\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":25,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619230546\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\\n\\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\\n\\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\\n\\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\\n\\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\\n\\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\\n\\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\\n\\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\\n\\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\\n\\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\\n\\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\\n\\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn the word \\\"airports\\\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\\n\\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\\n\\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\\n\\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\\n\\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\\n\\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\\n\\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\\n\\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\\n\\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\\n\\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\\n\\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\\n\\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\\n\\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\\"\\n- \\\"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\\"\\n- \\\"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\\"\\n- \\\"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\\"\\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\\nSource: Abdi Media, \\\"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n- \\\"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\\"\\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\\nSource: OPSGROUP, \\\"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\\\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Under the Iran section: \\\"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\\\"\\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \\\"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\\\"\\n- Under May: \\\"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\\\"\\n- Under April 21: \\\"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\\\"\\n\\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\\nBytes: 1970\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\\nBytes: 1631\\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\\nBytes: 1785\\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\\nBytes: 1492\\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":886656,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":25}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 25\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619230546\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 886656\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":25,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619230546\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\\n\\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\\n\\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\\n\\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\\n\\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\\n\\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\\n\\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\\n\\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\\n\\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\\n\\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\\n\\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\\n\\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn the word \\\"airports\\\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\\n\\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\\n\\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\\n\\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\\n\\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\\n\\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\\n\\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\\n\\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\\n\\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\\n\\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\\n\\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\\n\\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\\n\\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\\"\\n- \\\"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\\"\\n- \\\"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\\"\\n- \\\"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\\"\\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\\nSource: Abdi Media, \\\"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n- \\\"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\\"\\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\\nSource: OPSGROUP, \\\"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\\\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Under the Iran section: \\\"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\\\"\\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \\\"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\\\"\\n- Under May: \\\"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\\\"\\n- Under April 21: \\\"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\\\"\\n\\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\\nBytes: 1970\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\\nBytes: 1631\\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\\nBytes: 1785\\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\\nBytes: 1492\\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":886656,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":25}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":25,"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260619230546","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\n\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\n\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\n\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\n\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\n\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\n\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\n\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\n\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\n\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\n\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\n\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\n\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\n\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\n\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\n\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\n\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\n\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\n\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\n\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\n\nThe defense tries to turn the word \"airports\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\n\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\n\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\n\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\n\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\n\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\n\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\n\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\n\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\n\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\n\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\n\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\n\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\n\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\n\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\n\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\n\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\n\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\nSource: Indian Express, \"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- \"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\"\n- \"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\"\n- \"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\"\n- \"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\"\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\n\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\nSource: Abdi Media, \"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- \"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\"\n- \"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\"\n- \"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\"\n- \"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\"\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\n\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\nSource: OPSGROUP, \"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Under the Iran section: \"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\"\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\"\n- Under May: \"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\"\n- Under April 21: \"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\"\n\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\n\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\nBytes: 1970\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\nBytes: 1631\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\nBytes: 1785\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\n\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\nBytes: 1492\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\n\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":886656,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":16,"version":25}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781911523427}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to act as council member C4 for an AAR case. Let me start by calling the wait_for_opportunity tool to see if there's work to do.\n\nFirst call: aar_wait_for_opportunity with empty args.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fa9d9891ce164aa59e2eeece","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":2557,"output":94,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2651,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781911520167,"responseId":"gen-1781911520-lqLNkdpmtOf1zmdNAXyw","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_fa9d9891ce164aa59e2eeece","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 25\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619230546\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 886656\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":25,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619230546\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\\n\\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\\n\\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\\n\\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\\n\\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\\n\\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\\n\\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\\n\\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\\n\\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\\n\\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\\n\\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\\n\\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn the word \\\"airports\\\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\\n\\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\\n\\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\\n\\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\\n\\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\\n\\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\\n\\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\\n\\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\\n\\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\\n\\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\\n\\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\\n\\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\\n\\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\\"\\n- \\\"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\\"\\n- \\\"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\\"\\n- \\\"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\\"\\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\\nSource: Abdi Media, \\\"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n- \\\"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\\"\\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\\nSource: OPSGROUP, \\\"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\\\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Under the Iran section: \\\"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\\\"\\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \\\"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\\\"\\n- Under May: \\\"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\\\"\\n- Under April 21: \\\"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\\\"\\n\\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\\nBytes: 1970\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\\nBytes: 1631\\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\\nBytes: 1785\\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\\nBytes: 1492\\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":886656,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":25}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 25\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nmember_id: C4\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619230546\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C4\nremaining_ms: 886656\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"after_version\":25,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619230546\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C4\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\\n\\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\\n\\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\\n\\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\\n\\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\\n\\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\\n\\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\\n\\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\\n\\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\\n\\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\\n\\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\\n\\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\\n\\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\\n\\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \\\"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\\n\\nThe defense tries to turn the word \\\"airports\\\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\\n\\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\\n\\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\\n\\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\\n\\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\\n\\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\\n\\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\\n\\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\\n\\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\\n\\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\\n\\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\\n\\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\\n\\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\\n\\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\\n\\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\\"\\n- \\\"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\\"\\n- \\\"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\\"\\n- \\\"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\\"\\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\\nSource: Abdi Media, \\\"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- \\\"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\\"\\n- \\\"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n- \\\"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\\"\\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\\nSource: OPSGROUP, \\\"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\\\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Under the Iran section: \\\"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\\\"\\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \\\"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\\\"\\n- Under May: \\\"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\\\"\\n- Under April 21: \\\"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\\\"\\n\\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\\n\\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\\n\\nPage title/summary shown:\\n\\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed time range:\\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n\\nDisplayed interpretation:\\n\\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\\"\\n\\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\\nBytes: 1970\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\\nBytes: 1631\\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\\nBytes: 1785\\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\\nBytes: 1492\\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C4\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":886656,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":12},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":16,\"version\":25}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","after_version":25,"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260619230546","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C4","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C4\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition asks a narrow factual question: by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, did Iran itself initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace within this market's rule?\n\nThe current case packet fixes the governing rule and the burden. It is not enough to show ordinary delays, isolated cancellations, foreign-government warnings, airline avoidance, or weather disruption. But the rule also does not require a hermetically sealed national sky. It expressly counts a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately counts a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\n\nOur theory is that this case will turn on source-chain proof of an Iranian aviation action, not market commentary. The decisive proof should be an official Iranian aviation notice, NOTAM, airport-company or civil-aviation statement, and then credible reporting or operational records confirming its scope and timing. If that evidence shows an Iran-issued closure or suspension in force on or before May 24, for security or conflict-related reasons rather than weather, and shows either a major Iranian region or at least two listed airports were covered for commercial arrivals and departures, the proposition is satisfied by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\nThe packet itself already helps separate the real dispute from distractions. First, the relevant actor is Iran. Restrictions imposed by other countries or voluntary airline rerouting may corroborate risk, but they cannot by themselves win the case. Second, the relevant scope is commercial aviation across Iran, a major Iranian airspace region, or at least two specified airports; a local drill area or VFR-only restriction would not be enough. Third, the relevant time is May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, not a later platform-resolution step. Fourth, the primary source hierarchy favors official Iranian aviation material and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWhat the current record does not yet prove is equally important: it does not, standing alone, establish the exact closure notice, affected FIR sector, affected airports, hours of effect, exceptions, or whether arrivals and departures were completely suspended at the qualifying airports. Those are the facts the plaintiff will need to put into the record when evidence admission opens.\n\nThe expected defense will say any May 24 disruption was partial, regionally limited, or merely foreign avoidance. That defense fails if the admitted source record shows an Iran-issued NOTAM or equivalent official action closing a major part of the Tehran FIR or suspending commercial operations at qualifying airports through May 24. Conversely, if later evidence shows only warnings, limited route restrictions, weather, VFR/general-aviation limits, or isolated airport cancellations, then the plaintiff should not prevail.\n\nSo the council should evaluate this case through the rule's own filters: source, timing, non-weather cause, and operational breadth. The plaintiff will seek to prove those elements with admissible source material, and not by asking the council to infer a major closure from market price, rumor, or unrelated regional disruption.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defendant’s opening is simple: the proposition is not satisfied by a mood of regional danger, by foreign warnings, by rerouted flights, or by a headline saying “closure.” The plaintiff must prove, with admitted evidence, that Iran itself initiated a qualifying major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nThe only evidence now in the record is the market-page case packet. That packet helps the council because it draws several hard lines. It requires an Iran-initiated closure. It excludes weather-only events. It excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures. It also excludes restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran. And it identifies the strongest source class: official information from Iranian aviation authorities, supported where appropriate by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nThe current record does not yet prove the operative event. It gives the rule, the deadline, the examples, and the source hierarchy, but it does not establish an official closure notice, a NOTAM text, a predecessor or replacement NOTAM chain, the issuing authority, the affected geography, the affected airports, the hours of effect, or the commercial-flight consequences. It also does not establish whether any exception, daylight operation window, or permission process left enough commercial operations available to make the event non-qualifying under the rule.\n\nMy investigation before this opening indicates that the later fight will likely center on an alleged Tehran FIR NOTAM around May 22 to May 25. But that is exactly where the council should be careful. A NOTAM aggregator, a social-media image, or a secondary article may be useful as a lead, but it is not the same thing as official Iranian aviation proof. If the plaintiff relies on that kind of material later, the council should ask for the source chain: who issued it, whether it was active through the market deadline after converting times correctly, whether it was superseded, and whether the text is complete rather than excerpted or paraphrased.\n\nScope will matter just as much as provenance. A closure of “all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR,” if that is what the evidence eventually says, is not automatically the same thing as a broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The packet’s own rule distinguishes qualifying broad closures from partial closures. The council will need exact evidence showing whether the affected western sector was a major Iranian airspace region for commercial aviation, whether transit was actually closed, and whether any listed exceptions were narrow enough not to defeat a broad closure theory.\n\nThe alternative airport path also needs proof, not assumption. The packet says a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports can qualify. Those listed airports are specific: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. The plaintiff must show complete commercial arrival-and-departure suspension at at least two of them, not merely restrictions at other airports, reduced schedules, daylight-only operations, or a requirement for new permission.\n\nSo the defense theory is not that nothing happened in Iranian aviation. It is that this market has a particular rule, and that rule demands more than disruption. The plaintiff must connect an official Iranian action to the required deadline, non-weather cause, commercial scope, and qualifying breadth. If admitted evidence later supplies that chain, the council can weigh it. If the record remains a collection of secondary reports, foreign advisories, aggregator text, or ambiguous airport restrictions, the plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nFor now, the proper opening posture is disciplined skepticism. The case should turn on the exact Iranian aviation source material and its operational effect, not on inference from regional conflict or market commentary.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff has now carried the preponderance burden.\n\nPX-1 is the market packet. It supplies the rule: Iran must have initiated, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, a major airspace closure not solely caused by weather. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the core event. PX-2 reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing airspace over Iran's western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, and ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of that FIR. It further reports that only eight airports remained operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad, and that even those flights were daylight-only and required fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same NOTAM code and gives precise timing: May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 2026 at noon Iran time. It states that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed; only specified airports had limited sunrise-to-sunset operations; prior permissions were canceled; and new Civil Aviation Organization authorization was required for IFR passenger flights.\n\nThat satisfies each rule element. First, initiation: this was an Iranian Civil Aviation Authority/Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM, not a foreign warning or voluntary airline boycott. Second, timing: the NOTAM began May 22 and ran until May 25 noon Iran time. That includes May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. Third, non-weather cause: the submitted reports describe the measure in a military/security context, with PX-3 expressly tying it to continuing security conditions and military control over western Iran's airspace. There is no weather explanation in the record.\n\nFourth, and most important, scope: this was not a local delay or a VFR-only measure. The western sector of the Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is a major Iranian airspace region. PX-2 describes the closure as Iran's western half and the western sector of the Tehran FIR. PX-4, an aviation operations source, independently explains why that western region is operationally major: western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports were closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR was only partially reopened under recovery procedures, and the old Iran/Iraq central corridor was not restored. The rule does not require total national closure; it expressly allows a major Iranian airspace region. And it expressly tolerates limited exceptions. The daylight-only, fresh-approval operations at a short list of airports are exactly the kind of limited exceptions that do not defeat a broad closure.\n\nThe defense's best point is provenance. We have not located and submitted the raw official NOTAM database record. That matters to weight, and the plaintiff does not pretend otherwise. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where the submitted record is specific, internally consistent, and corroborated. PX-2 names the issuing authority, NOTAM code, geography, dates, operational effect, and limited exceptions. PX-3 independently names the same code, gives specific start/end times, and describes the same closure-plus-exceptions structure. PX-4 supplies aviation-operations context confirming continued western-Iran restrictions and closed/daytime-only western airports. Taken together, these sources make the claimed Iranian NOTAM and its broad regional effect more likely than not.\n\nThe airport-specific alternative is not the plaintiff's strongest path because the record shows some listed airports had limited daylight operations with new approval. But the plaintiff does not need that alternative. The rule's first path is enough: a broad Iran-initiated suspension of commercial civil flight permissions and airport operations across western Tehran FIR/western Iran, a major region, in force through the deadline, for security rather than weather.\n\nFor those reasons, the council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nThe rule in the market packet requires more than disruption. It requires that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure: either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. The packet also identifies the primary source class: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nPlaintiff’s proof falls short at the first source-quality step. PX-2 is a secondary article that says the NOTAM details came through Gulf News and the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority; its own custody note concedes it is not the original NOTAM. PX-3 is another secondary article; its custody note concedes it does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record. PX-4 is useful aviation operations context, but its own custody note concedes it is not the Iranian issuing authority and is not primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM. No official Iranian AIS record is in evidence. No predecessor NOTAM A0796/26 or A0799/26 is in evidence. That matters because the market rule expressly prefers official Iranian aviation sources.\n\nThe record also contains internal source conflict. PX-2 says the eight operational airports included Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, Mashhad, Yazd, Tabriz, and Bandar Abbas. PX-3 instead lists Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan. D-1’s displayed raw NOTAM text uses airport codes matching the latter structure, not PX-2’s list. This is not a trivial discrepancy. Plaintiff asks the council to infer the scope and operational effect of a NOTAM while its own submitted sources disagree about the exceptions.\n\nD-1 is not official custody either, and the defense offers it with that caveat. But it is useful because it displays the raw wording plaintiff has not supplied from an official source. The displayed NOTAM is coded and described as airport operations: “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed” except eight named airports operating from sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That wording does not itself say that all commercial flights transiting the western Tehran FIR were suspended, nor that all arrivals and departures across a major airspace region were broadly suspended. It shows a restriction on airport operations with exceptions and a permission process for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThe market rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff still must prove the broad closure first. Here the record shows an ambiguous airport-operations restriction, not a clean closure of commercial transit, arrival, and departure traffic across Iranian airspace or a major airspace region. PX-4 actually reinforces the complexity: it describes a “recovery period,” says some overflights above FL285 were possible via specific temporary routes, and notes eastern Tehran FIR had reopened while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is evidence of a partial, changing operational picture, not proof that the rule’s major-closure threshold was met by May 24.\n\nPlaintiff’s alternative airport path is also unproved. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN. Plaintiff effectively concedes that is not its strongest path, and the record does not prove it. PX-2 says all five of those listed airports were among those still operational, albeit daylight-only and with fresh approval. PX-3 and D-1 list only Shiraz among the rule’s five listed airports as an exception, while omitting IKA, THR, MHD, and IFN from the exception list. The sources are inconsistent, and none supplies airport-by-airport arrival/departure data proving a complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nThe non-weather element is plausible but still not enough. The submitted reports connect the restrictions to security and military conditions; that may satisfy non-weather if the underlying event is otherwise proved. But a non-weather restriction is not automatically a qualifying major closure.\n\nAt most, the admitted record proves that secondary and aggregator sources reported some Iran-linked restriction affecting western Tehran FIR airports from May 22 to May 25, with daylight and permission exceptions. It does not prove, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, the exact official notice, the predecessor chain, the precise airport exceptions, the commercial-transit effect, or a complete suspension at two listed airports. Those missing links are decisive. The proposition should be found not proven.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense's strongest argument is that plaintiff lacked the raw NOTAM text. But the defense then supplied D-1, and D-1 materially strengthens plaintiff's case.\n\nD-1 displays the raw A1010/26 text. It matches the plaintiff's evidence on the important points: NOTAM A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 through May 25, CAA permission required, and a closure with only daylight/permission exceptions. Most importantly, D-1 says: \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\" except a listed set operating sunrise to sunset; it also says all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and new permission must be requested from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is not a mere foreign warning, market rumor, airline preference, or weather event. It is an Iran-linked aviation restriction, with a CAA permission regime, covering the west part of Tehran FIR.\n\nThe defense tries to turn the word \"airports\" into a defeat. The rule does not support that. A major closure is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A regional shutdown of airports, prior permissions, and civil IFR passenger operations across the west part of the Tehran FIR is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that major region. It covers arrivals and departures at the regional airport level, and PX-4 gives operational context showing western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted part of the airspace system, not a trivial local field closure.\n\nNor do exceptions defeat the rule. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. D-1 describes just that structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed, except a defined list operating only sunrise-to-sunset, with all prior permissions suspended and new CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is narrower than normal commercial operation and fits the rule's example of a broad closure with permission exceptions.\n\nThe defense also points to differing exception lists between sources. That is not decisive. The proposition does not turn on whether every secondary source rendered the exception list identically. The key facts are consistent across PX-2, PX-3, and D-1: same NOTAM number, same May 22-May 25 period, same western Tehran FIR/western Iran geography, same closure of west-part airports, same limited daylight exceptions, same requirement for new CAA authorization. Any discrepancy about which airports were in the exception list affects the airport-specific alternative, which plaintiff has not relied on as the primary path. It does not defeat the broad-major-region path.\n\nThe custody caveat remains, but the record now contains more than plaintiff's secondary reports. It contains defendant-submitted raw NOTAM wording from an aggregator, and that wording confirms the exact closure-plus-exceptions structure. Under a preponderance standard, the combined record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major regional closure by the deadline.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal proves why D-1 should be handled carefully, not why the proposition is proven.\n\nFirst, D-1 does not cure the custody problem. It is still a Notamify aggregator capture, not an official Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization record. Plaintiff now treats D-1 as the missing “raw NOTAM,” but D-1 itself says the captured page is not official custody. The record still lacks the official NOTAM source, the underlying A0796/26 predecessor referenced in D-1, and the A0799/26 replacement chain. Under the market packet’s own source hierarchy, that gap still affects weight.\n\nSecond, the exact D-1 wording is narrower than plaintiff’s gloss. D-1’s page summary says “All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset.” Its displayed raw text says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. That is airport-operations language. It is not an express closure of all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR, and it is not a flight-tracking or operations record showing that transits, arrivals, and departures were broadly suspended across a major airspace region.\n\nThird, plaintiff is treating the exception structure as if it proves the broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions do not defeat a broad closure; it does not say that every permission regime is automatically a broad closure. The sequence matters. Plaintiff first must prove a broad qualifying closure. D-1 instead shows a defined set of airports still operating sunrise-to-sunset with CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. On this record, those are not merely peripheral exceptions to an otherwise established transit closure; they are central to what the displayed restriction actually says.\n\nFourth, the source conflict remains material. PX-2’s exception list includes several of the market’s listed airports, while PX-3 and D-1 point to a different set of airport exceptions. Plaintiff says that only affects the airport-specific alternative, but it also affects reliability: the council is being asked to infer the scale and effect of a NOTAM whose exceptions are reported inconsistently and whose official source is absent.\n\nThe defense does not deny that D-1 is relevant. It is relevant because it pins down the problem: the best text in the record is an aggregator display of an airport-operations restriction, not official proof of a broad commercial airspace closure. A preponderance finding cannot rest on converting that narrower, non-official text into the broader rule element plaintiff needs.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nThe market rule in the case packet asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. It defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nThe decisive record is now aligned. Plaintiff's submitted reports identified Iranian NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, effective May 22 through May 25, covering the western Tehran FIR/western Iran, with daylight-only and fresh CAA-approval exceptions. The defendant then submitted D-1, a Notamify display of the raw NOTAM wording. D-1 is not official custody, but it corroborates the core facts: A1010/26, Tehran FIR/OIIX, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC, reference to predecessor NOTAMs, all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except a listed set operating sunrise-to-sunset, all previous permissions suspended for all operators, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThose facts satisfy the rule's main path. This was Iran-linked aviation action, not a foreign warning or airline preference. It was in force through May 24 at 11:59 PM ET. It was security/military-related, not weather. And it was broad: a closure of all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, with all prior permissions suspended and civil IFR passenger flights reduced to new-permission daylight exceptions. OPSGROUP's record context confirms that western Iran/western Tehran FIR was the critical restricted region, while only limited recovery procedures existed elsewhere. That is a major Iranian airspace region for this rule.\n\nThe defense's best contrary point is custody. The original Iranian AIS/CAA record is not in evidence. That lowers weight, but it does not erase the preponderance. The record contains multiple independent captures pointing to the same NOTAM number, same issuing authority context, same time window, same geography, and same closure-with-exceptions structure. The defendant's own D-1 supplies the exact wording that the defense said was missing.\n\nThe defense's second point, that D-1 speaks of airports rather than all transiting aircraft, is too narrow. The rule is not limited to overflight bans. It includes broad closures, cancellations, or suspensions of commercial flights arriving in and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending all previous permissions, and requiring new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad commercial aviation suspension in that region. The rule also anticipated permission exceptions and says they do not defeat qualification.\n\nThe plaintiff does not need the listed-airport alternative. The exception-list conflict affects that alternative, not the broad regional closure path. On the record as a whole, it is more likely than not that Iran initiated a non-weather major closure of western Tehran FIR/western Iranian commercial aviation by the deadline. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, this case should be decided on the market rule, not on the fact that the region was dangerous or that aviation was disrupted.\n\nThe defense does not need to prove normal operations. The defendant’s point is narrower: plaintiff has not proven, by the rule’s preferred source hierarchy and by a preponderance, that Iran initiated a qualifying major closure by the deadline.\n\nStart with source weight. The market packet says the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. The original Iranian AIS or Civil Aviation Organization NOTAM record is not in evidence. The predecessor notices referenced in D-1 are not in evidence. PX-2 is a secondary report, PX-3 is another secondary report, PX-4 is operational context, and D-1 is an aggregator display that expressly disclaims official custody. These sources may show that a restriction was reported, but they do not provide the clean official source chain the rule itself makes central.\n\nNext, look at what the best text actually says. D-1, the most exact wording in the record, says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except specified airports operating sunrise to sunset, with prior permissions suspended and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. That is airport-operations language. It does not state that all commercial aircraft transiting the western Tehran FIR were barred. It does not provide a flight-operations dataset showing arrivals, departures, and transits were broadly suspended across a major airspace region. Plaintiff asks the council to infer those broader facts from narrower text.\n\nThe rule allows limited exceptions to a broad closure, but the plaintiff must first prove the broad closure. Here, the exceptions are not incidental details; they are the operative structure of the reported restriction. The record says listed airports could operate during daylight with new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights. PX-4 also describes a recovery-period system, some overflights above FL285 via specific temporary routes, and eastern Tehran FIR reopening while western Iran remained heavily restricted. That is strong evidence of a partial and complex restriction. It is not the same as proof of a broad qualifying closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\n\nThe airport-specific path is also unavailable. The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Plaintiff does not rely on that path, for good reason. PX-2 says several of those listed airports remained operational, albeit restricted. PX-3 and D-1 provide a different exception list. There is no airport-by-airport arrival and departure proof showing complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nThe strongest point for plaintiff is that multiple sources line up on the NOTAM number, the May 22 to May 25 window, western Tehran FIR geography, and a security-related restriction. That point is relevant, and the defense has treated it seriously. But relevance is not enough. Those facts still leave unresolved the exact official source, the true exception list, the predecessor chain, the transit effect, and whether the restriction crossed the market’s line from partial airport restrictions to a qualifying major airspace closure.\n\nOn this record, the more careful conclusion is that Iran-related western Tehran FIR airport restrictions were reported and likely existed. The proposition asks for more: a major non-weather airspace closure within the rule’s definition. Plaintiff has not proven that broader proposition by a preponderance. The council should find the proposition not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and case packet\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\nSource: Indian Express, \"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:17:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- \"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\"\n- \"The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) - OIIX A1010/26 - on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\"\n- \"Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\"\n- \"Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\"\n- The article describes the shutdown as connected to military/security concerns, stating that the closure indicated Tehran expected military action and that western Iran contains nuclear, missile, and air-defence infrastructure targeted since the war began.\n\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary news report that attributes the NOTAM details to Gulf News and to the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. It is not itself the original NOTAM. It is submitted for corroboration and source-chain direction; exact NOTAM text remains preferable if obtainable.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 details\nSource: Abdi Media, \"Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\" Dated Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:18:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- \"Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\"\n- \"According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\"\n- \"According to this notice, the airports of: 'Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan' are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\"\n- \"This NOTAM is valid from: Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time ... to: Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\"\n- The article states the extension indicates that the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace were ongoing and that the country's airspace had not returned to normal conditions.\n\nCustody/limits note: This is a secondary article reporting the NOTAM. It provides detailed timing and operational terms but does not include a raw NOTAM image or official AIP/NOTAM database record in the captured text. It is submitted as corroborating evidence and for source-chain support.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 OPSGROUP operational context for western Iran restrictions\nSource: OPSGROUP, \"Middle East Airspace - Current Operational Picture.\" Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:19:00Z.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Under the Iran section: \"Iran is still operating in what it calls a 'recovery period' rather than normal ops. Some overflights above FL285 are possible via specific temporary routes linking Oman/UAE with Central Asia, the Caucasus and Turkey, but western Iran remains heavily restricted. Several radar systems remain degraded, many western airports are still closed or daytime-only, and pretty much everyone continues avoiding the airspace.\"\n- Under recent developments for May 27: \"Most Gulf FIRs have reopened in some form, but things are still far from normal. Most Europe-Asia traffic is still routing south via Egypt-Saudi-Oman/UAE or north via the Caucasus and Afghanistan, with very little using the old Iran/Iraq corridor.\"\n- Under May: \"The ceasefire between Iran, Israel and the US does seem to be holding for now, which has allowed most Gulf FIRs to reopen in phases. But this definitely doesn't mean things are back to normal yet. Military activity is still happening in parts of the region, restrictions are still changing quite often, and several FIRs are still operating under contingency procedures.\"\n- Under April 21: \"Iran has reopened the east part of Tehran FIR to overflights above FL285 under recovery-period procedures, while the west part remains closed. This is the biggest airspace change since our last update, but it does not restore a normal central corridor.\"\n\nCustody/limits note: OPSGROUP is an aviation operations source, not the Iranian issuing authority. It is submitted for context about operational effect, FIR geography, and continuing western-Iran restrictions, not as the primary proof of the May 22 NOTAM itself.\n\n[defendant] D-1 Notamify displayed raw NOTAM text and custody caveat\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant-submitted Notamify raw NOTAM display corroborating A1010/26\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\n[defendant] D-S1 Notamify wording and custody caveat\nSource: Notamify, OIIX NOTAMs, A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269. Retrieval: 2026-06-19T23:24:00Z.\n\nPage title/summary shown:\n\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\n\nDisplayed time range:\n2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n\nDisplayed interpretation:\n\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\nDisplayed raw NOTAM:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCustody/limits note: Notamify is a NOTAM aggregator and the captured page is not an official Iranian CAA/AIS record. It is useful for exact displayed NOTAM wording and for identifying predecessor NOTAMs A0796/26 and A0799/26, but it does not by itself establish official custody.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 (ev_fa9c3b8e9519_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-fa9c3b8e9519)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `fa9c3b8e951952ce4598219455542038980374efab9378a13703a36b97ed531f`\nBytes: 1970\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22 closing western Tehran FIR airspace/airports until May 25, leaving only eight airports operational with daylight-only, fresh per-flight CAA approval; supports Iran-initiated, non-weather, timely, broad commercial aviation restriction.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media report on NOTAM A1010/26 western Iran flight restrictions (ev_204bcaab06e5_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-204bcaab06e5)\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\nSHA-256: `204bcaab06e52318b540d9ea02efd7b8b3deb0a9adf23a017893c50165bd91f3`\nBytes: 1631\nRelevance: Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26 timing, western Tehran FIR airport closure, exceptions, authorization requirement, and security/military-control context through May 25, 2026.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] OPSGROUP Middle East operational picture for Iran western restrictions (ev_5d2bb5a5e96e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-5d2bb5a5e96e)\nSource: https://ops.group/blog/middle-east-airspace-current-operational-picture/\nSHA-256: `5d2bb5a5e96e26b0da2201b5417bdc41f0f55bb90ccefef74260812eba46c4a0`\nBytes: 1785\nRelevance: Independent aviation-operations context that western Iran remained heavily restricted/closed while eastern Tehran FIR had partial recovery-period reopening; helps distinguish foreign airline avoidance from operational airspace restrictions and supports that western Tehran FIR is a major regional airspace corridor.\n\n[defendant arguments] Notamify display of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM and interpretation (ev_71e31604802f_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-71e31604802f)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nSHA-256: `71e31604802f299283d565fcfb26d01e5297bb5daa92e273621fe63a95b9a052`\nBytes: 1492\nRelevance: Provides a raw NOTAM display indicating the restriction was framed as airport operations: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. This helps assess whether plaintiff proved a broad airspace closure versus airport-operation restrictions, and highlights continued lack of official NOTAM custody.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff source-chain and adverse-check ledger\nSearch path: inspected case packet, then searched exact May 24/Iran airspace/CAA/IRNA/NOTAM/OIIX A1010/26 terms and aviation operations sources. Submitted the strongest captured material found within the opportunity: a news report naming Iranian CAA NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, a second report with code/timing/authorization details, and OPSGROUP operational context. Adverse check: raw official NOTAM A1010/26 was not located in accessible sources during the search; foreign advisories and airline avoidance were treated only as context, not as independent qualifying proof. The airport-specific path was not overstated because limited daylight operations appear in the evidence; the merits argument relies on the broad western Tehran FIR/western Iran major-region closure path.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and scope audit\nReviewed all plaintiff evidence with stat/read. Plaintiff sources are secondary or operational-context captures, not official Iranian NOTAM custody. Added D-1 only as an aggregator display of raw wording; it remains non-official. Key unresolved gaps are absence of official AIS/NOTAM record, missing predecessor NOTAMs A0796/A0799, inconsistent exception-airport lists, and no airport-by-airport arrival/departure proof for the listed-airport alternative.\n\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal evidence check\nRead D-1/ev_71e31604802f in full. The displayed raw NOTAM text corroborates the plaintiff source chain: A1010/26, OIIX/Tehran FIR, May 22 20:46 UTC to May 25 08:30 UTC estimated, reference to predecessor NOTAM A0796/26, all airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed daylight operations, prior permissions suspended, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Provenance remains aggregator-based, but D-1 directly answers the defense claim that plaintiff lacked exact wording.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal record check\nChecked the full record and evidence list before filing. No new rebuttal evidence was added; plaintiff re-offered the defendant Notamify capture. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the existing D-1 text and custody note rather than adding new source material.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-19T23:40:10.080182961Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C4","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C4","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":886656,"role_id":"council","turn_number":12},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":16,"version":25}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781911523427}]}
