n the western sector of the Tehran FIR. Only 8 airports remained operational with daylight-only operations and fresh per-flight approval required.\n\n**PX-3** (Abdi Media): Corroborates NOTAM A1010/26, provides timing (May 22, 00:16 Iran time through May 25, 12:00 noon Iran time), states all airports in western Tehran FIR closed, only specified airports operating sunrise-to-sunset, prior permissions canceled, new authorization required.\n\n**PX-4** (OPSGROUP): Aviation operations context showing western Iran remained heavily restricted, many western airports closed or daytime-only, east Tehran FIR partially reopened.\n\n**D-1** (Notamify): Displays raw NOTAM text:\n- A1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\n- Effective: 2026-05-22 20:46 UTC to 2026-05-25 08:30 UTC (estimated)\n\n\n- All airports in west part of Tehran FIR closed except 8 specific airports operating sunrise to sunset\n- All previous permissions suspended for all operators\n- New permission required from CAA for civil IFR passenger flights\n\nThe timing works—the NOTAM window (May 22 20:46 UTC through May 25 08:30 UTC) encompasses May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET (which is May 25, 06:59 UTC on May 25).\n\nThis was an Iran-initiated restriction through their aviation authorities, not weather-related but tied to security and military conditions, and it was in effect at the deadline.\n\nThe key issue is whether this qualifies as a \"major closure.\" The restriction covered all airports in the western Tehran FIR with only 8 exceptions operating under limited daylight conditions and requiring fresh CAA approval. All prior permissions were suspended. While the NOTAM language focuses on airports rather than explicitly stating all transiting flights were barred, the practical effect of closing all airports in a major FIR region with suspended permissions and new authorization requirements represents a substantial closure of commercial aviation operations in that area.\n\nThe defense challenges this on several grounds: the evidence comes from aggregators rather than official Iranian aviation sources, the predecessor NOTAMs aren't in the record, the wording emphasizes airport closures rather than airspace closure, exception lists vary across sources, and there's no flight data demonstrating actual commercial traffic suspension. However, under preponderance of the evidence, multiple independent sources corroborate the same NOTAM number, time window, geographic scope, and closure structure. The defendant's own submitted evidence confirms the core facts about the western FIR closure with daylight exceptions and new CAA authorization requirements. While official Iranian AIS records would strengthen the case, the converging evidence from multiple sources supports that a qualifying major closure occurred. The NOTAM's operational effect—suspending all prior permissions and restricting operations to daylight hours with fresh CAA approval—constitutes a broad commercial suspension in a major region, which satisfies the rule even with limited exceptions permitted. Given that multiple sources corroborate the same NOTAM details and timing, and the rule explicitly allows for narrow exceptions, the preponderance of evidence supports that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by the deadline.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning","type":"thinking"},{"text":" Summary:**\n-","type":"text"}],"model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1781911523-3AHRWaUWEtDkaCgqJYPu","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216","role":"assistant","stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1781911523430,"usage":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":0,"output":0,"totalTokens":0}},"type":"message_update"}
